Bayesian First Aid Examples

binom.test

A classical binomial test:

binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.01182
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5634 0.9427
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

Prepend binom.test by bfa. to run the Bayesian “version”.

bfa.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.773 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.601 0.93 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.996 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.004

The idea is to respect the arguments to the original binom.test as far as possible. For example, setting p and conf.level as in…

binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.7977
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.75
## 80 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6393 0.9098
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

… is respected by bfa.binom.test:

bfa.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.771 
## 80% credible interval:
##   0.676 0.897 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.75 by a probability of 0.623 
## and less than 0.75 by a probability of 0.377

By assigning the result of bfa.binom.test to a variable we can get some more useful info by calling plot for looking at the posterior (and perhaps a posterior predictive check), summary for a more extensive summary than the standard print out above, and diagnostics for MCMC diagnostics. The idea is that the behavior of these functions should be consistent for all the bfa.*.test functions. 

(fit <- bfa.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20))

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.772 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.599 0.931 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.996 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.004

plot(fit)


summary(fit)

##   Data
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: The relative frequency of success
## x_pred: Predicted number of successes in a replication
## 
##   Measures
##          mean    sd  HDIlo  HDIup %<comp %>comp
## theta   0.772 0.087  0.599  0.931  0.004  0.996
## x_pred 15.431 2.531 10.000 19.000  0.000  1.000
## 
## 'HDIlo' and 'HDIup' are the limits of a 95% HDI credible interval.
## '%<comp' and '%>comp' are the probabilities of the respective parameter being
## smaller or larger than 0.5.
## 
##   Quantiles
##         q2.5%   q25% median   q75% q97.5%
## theta   0.577  0.718  0.779  0.836  0.917
## x_pred 10.000 14.000 16.000 17.000 20.000

diagnostics(fit)

## 
## Iterations = 1:5000
## Thinning interval = 1 
## Number of chains = 3 
## Sample size per chain = 5000 
## 
##   Diagnostic measures
##          mean    sd mcmc_se n_eff Rhat
## theta   0.772 0.087   0.001 15000    1
## x_pred 15.431 2.531   0.021 15000    1
## 
## mcmc_se: the estimated standard error of the MCMC approximation of the mean.
## n_eff: a crude measure of effective MCMC sample size.
## Rhat: the potential scale reduction factor (at convergence, Rhat=1).
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: The relative frequency of success
## x_pred: Predicted number of successes in a replication

Of course, in the case of bfa.binom.test the MCMC diagnostics might be a bit silly…

t.test

The alternative for the t.test is of course BEST.

x <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 2, sd = 5)
t.test(x)

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x
## t = 1.97, df = 29, p-value = 0.05842
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.06713  3.59610
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     1.764

bfa.t.test(x)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.739 [-0.238, 3.505]
## sd of x: 4.958 [3.587, 6.42]
## 
## The mean is more than 0 by a probability of 0.965 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.035

bfa.t.test also respects the arguments of the original t.test.

y <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5)
bfa.t.test(x, y, mu = 1, conf.level = 0.5)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x and y
## 
##   Estimates [50% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.718 [1.039, 2.291]
## mean of y: 10.87 [10.37, 11.42]
## difference of the means: -9.153 [-9.998, -8.333]
## sd of x: 4.979 [4.304, 5.248]
## sd of y: 4.186 [3.655, 4.442]
## 
## The difference of the means is more than 1 by a probability of 0 
## and less than 1 by a probability of 1

Or even…

# Creating 'paired' data
d <- data.frame(x = rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5), group = rep(c("A", "B"), 
    15))

bfa.t.test(x ~ group, paired = T, data = d)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x by group
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean paired difference: 0.07 [-3.32, 3.432]
## sd of the paired differences: 6.274 [3.787, 9.007]
## 
## The mean difference is more than 0 by a probability of 0.52 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.48

The same generic functions (plot, summary, diagnostics) works for all fitted models from bfa.t.test.

Output one sample bfa.t.test
